    "body": "### Problem\n\nSo it's my bad I would even say it help me catch a bug in my terminal emulator but that didn't happen before I updated nvim to 0.12 so I was surprised\n\nIn nvim/tui/termkey/driver-csi.c:\n\n```c\nstatic TermKeyResult peekkey_csi_csi(TermKey *tk, TermKeyCsi *csi, size_t introlen, TermKeyKey *key,\n                                     int force, size_t *nbytep) /// L 714\n{\n  unsigned cmd;\n  TermKeyResult ret = parse_csi(tk, introlen, &csi_len, params, &nparams, &cmd);\n ...\n  // We know from the logic above that cmd must be >= 0x40 and < 0x80\n  /// This comment is kinda misleading we only know cmd & 0xff must be >= 0x40 and < 0x80\n  \n  if (csi_handlers[(cmd & 0xff) - 0x40]) {\n    result = (*csi_handlers[(cmd & 0xff) - 0x40])(tk, key, (int)cmd, params, (int)nparams);\n  }\n ...\n}\n\nstatic TermKeyResult parse_csi(TermKey *tk, size_t introlen, size_t *csi_len,\n                               TermKeyCsiParam params[], size_t *nargs, unsigned *commandp) //L 459\n{\n  unsigned char cmd = CHARAT(csi_end);\n  *commandp = cmd; /// So here that's true for *commandp\n\n  ...\n    // See if there is an initial byte\n  if (CHARAT(p) >= '<' && CHARAT(p) <= '?') {\n    *commandp |= (unsigned)(CHARAT(p) << 8); /// But here \n    p++;\n  }\n  // Now attempt to parse out up number;number;... separated values\n  while (p < csi_end) {\n    ...\n     } else if (c >= 0x20 && c <= 0x2f) {\n      *commandp |= (unsigned)(c << 16); /// And here it's getting way outside the char range\n      break;\n    }\n   ...\n}\n```\n\nand so because my misinterpretation of the xterm doc I ended up sending ESC P 1$rm instead of 0x90 1$rm for a DCS response\ncausing a segfault inside:\n\n```c\nstatic TermKeyResult handle_csi_ss3_full(TermKey *tk, TermKeyKey *key, int cmd,\n                                         TermKeyCsiParam *params, int nparams) /// L 25\n{\n  ...\n  key->type = csi_ss3s[cmd - 0x40].type; /// Here I access the array out of range \n                                             /// because cmd = 0x240050 ('$' << 16 + 'P')\n  key->code.sym = csi_ss3s[cmd - 0x40].sym;\n  key->modifiers &= ~(csi_ss3s[cmd - 0x40].modifier_mask);\n  key->modifiers |= csi_ss3s[cmd - 0x40].modifier_set;\n}\n```\nThat was my fault and for a valid SS3 sequence that shouldn't happen but I'm thinking perhaps putting cmd &= 0xff at the top of handle_csi_ss3_full and potentially in other handler could avoid UB down the line\n\nI don't know sorry to bother you can close it if you want.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnot sure that could be reproduce like that it's my terminal fault but perhaps it could happen normally\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNot crashing and idk perhaps that could lead to ACE\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.3\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno vim 9.2.2026\n\n### Operating system/version\n\n7.0.12-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nvultty 0.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nsystem package manager (pacman)",
